snippet.textDisplay: I thought AMD said this when the 3,000 series first launched, it was the 3rd gen chip at that point. On top of people being mad NOW  being dumb, I think it's really dumb to be mad in the first place. The mobos lasted 3 generations, and current motherboards and the b550 will still work, anyone who upgraded platforms for the 3000 series are still set, the only people "screwed" are those who cheaped out when getting a 3rd gen, or people who have been sitting on their CPU for like 2+ years already. Which at that point, you're not planning to upgrade for a while anyway because hey if your 2nd gen was fine when 3rd gen came out, its gonna be just fine for uses when 4th gen comes out, unless suddenly you want the updates that come with a new architure--which would take a new motherboard to support it anyways.

snippet.textDisplay:
The recently unveiled 400 series boards from Intel will support 11th gen CPUs. AM4 boards won't support Zen 4, and AMD is telling me to replace my B450 Tomahawk MAX with a B550 board? That's not happening. 
I'm not hoping to put a Ryzen 4000 in my Tomahawk MAX board, cause I WILL definitely put a Ryzen 4000 chip in my motherboard. If that's not possible, I'm switching back to Intel. You can't delay the B550 chipset for a whole year and expect people to happily buy your Ryzen 4000 CPUs, while you give the middle finger to their B450 boards. 

My B450 board has a massive 32MB BIOS chip whereas some X570 boards have a 16MB chip. Those 👏 BIOS 👏capacity👏 limitations👏 are 👏bullshit. You can even drop zen 1 support on non-MAX boards and squeeze zen 3 support in their BIOSes.
